    "summary": "The Sumerian King List is an ancient cuneiform document, composed around 2100–2000 BC, that enumerates the dynasties and rulers of Sumerian city-states from mythological antediluvian times to the historical period near its date of composition. The text begins with kings who supposedly reigned for tens of thousands of years before a great flood, then transitions to more plausible reign lengths as the list approaches the historical era. The document presents kingship as a single institution that passed sequentially between cities — Eridu, Kish, Uruk, Ur, and others — rather than existing simultaneously in multiple centers, reflecting an ideological claim about political legitimacy rather than historical fact.\n\nDespite its legendary elements, the Sumerian King List preserves genuine historical information about rulers from the mid-third millennium BC onward. Cross-referencing the list with other documents, including contemporary inscriptions from the [[event:1724|Third Dynasty of Ur]] period, has allowed scholars to reconstruct a reliable chronological framework for Mesopotamian history from roughly 2600 BC onward. The text also names figures such as Gilgamesh of Uruk and Enmebaragesi of Kish, who are attested in other sources, demonstrating that the later portions of the list drew on genuine historical tradition. The Sumerian King List remains one of the most studied documents in ancient Near Eastern scholarship.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sumerian_King_List",
